observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:

LCE ensure that 
cash disbursing function is performed only by duly designated Disbursing Officers; and 


stop the practice of granting cash advances to elected officials other than for their traveling expenses;

Special Disbursing Officers/Accountable Officers refrain from transferring their cash advance to other officials/employees pursuant to Section 4.1.6 of COA Circular No. 97-02;

Municipal Accountant 


 regularly remind all officials/employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period and ensure that all cash advances are fully liquidated at the end of each year; 


itemize all cash advances of an officer/employee and provide complete/detailed information in the RUCA and Liquidation Reports for a more effective monitoring of CAs and to easily match liquidations with the corresponding CAs;  and 



 thoroughly review all claims for his approval to ensure the completeness of documents supporting its regularity and validity; and

Municipal Treasurer ensure that all payments are made by check except in certain instances when it may be very difficult, impractical, or impossible to make payments by check pursuant to Section 2 of COA Circular No. 97-02.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer ensure that only the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF at yearend are transferred to the Special Trust Fund pursuant to Section 5.1.10 COA Circular No. 2012-002;

Municipal Accountant:

 strictly adhere with the provisions of Section 5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 on the accounting and reporting guidelines for LDRRMF; 



ensure that the amount and details of the Unexpended Balance of LDRRMF are disclosed in the Notes to Financial Statements; and

ensure that transfers of unexpended balances of the 5% LDRRMF from the GF to the TF are duly supported with schedules and computations;

recognize PPE amounting to ₱310,000.00 in the books of accounts; and 


Municipal Accountant in coordination with the General Services Officer, determine if the items of inventory in Finding No. 3 had already been issued or distributed to the end-users. Unissued items shall be recognized as inventory in the TF books. If all items had been issued, no adjusting entry is necessary; and


LDRRMO submit the CY 2020 LDRRMFIP to the Audit Team and ensure its regular submission for audit purposes.

We recommended that the:
LCE (a) ensure that cash disbursing function is performed only by duly designated Disbursing Officers; and (b) stop the practice of granting cash advances to elected officials other than for their traveling expenses;
Special Disbursing Officers/Accountable Officers refrain from transferring their cash advance to other officials/employees pursuant to Section 4.1.6 of COA Circular No. 97-02;
Municipal Accountant (a) regularly remind all officials/employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period and ensure that all cash advances are fully liquidated at the end of each year; (b) itemize all cash advances of an officer/employee and provide complete/detailed information in the RUCA and Liquidation Reports for a more effective monitoring of CAs and to easily match liquidations with the corresponding CAs;  and (c) thoroughly review all claims  for his approval to ensure the completeness of documents supporting its regularity and validity; and
Municipal Treasurer ensure that all payments are made by check except in certain instances when it may be very difficult, impractical, or impossible to make payments by check pursuant to Section 2 of COA Circular No. 97-02.
In its written reply, the Management committed to comply with the audit recommendations.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer ensure that only the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF at yearend are transferred to the Special Trust Fund pursuant to Section 5.1.10 COA Circular No. 2012-002;
Municipal Accountant (i) strictly adhere with the provisions of Section 5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 on the accounting and reporting guidelines for LDRRMF; (ii) ensure that the amount and details of the Unexpended Balance of LDRRMF are disclosed in the Notes to Financial Statements; and (iii) ensure that transfers of unexpended balances of the 5% LDRRMF from the GF to the TF are duly supported with schedules and computations;
Municipal Accountant (a) recognize PPE amounting to ₱310,000.00 in the books of accounts; and (b) in coordination with the General Services Officer, determine if the items of inventory in Finding No. 3 had already been issued or distributed to the end-users. Unissued items shall be recognized as inventory in the TF books. If all items had been issued, no adjusting entry is necessary; and
LDRRMO submit the CY 2020 LDRRMFIP to the Audit Team and ensure its regular submission for audit purposes.
According to the management's written response to the Audit Team, compliance with the audit recommendations shall be observed. As a matter of fact, Management revisited the guidelines on the proper use and reportorial requirements of the LDRRMF. As regards the audit finding on the non-submission the CY 2020 LDRRMFIP, the said investment plan was submitted to the Audit Team on August 24, 2021.

We recommended that the:

1.    LCE, through the Municipal Accountant, (a) serve written notices to all concerned accountable officers requiring settlement of the outstanding cash advances and institute legal action against them, if warranted; and (b) ensure that all concerned officers and employees strictly comply with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 97-002 and P.D. No. 1445 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and the Revised I.R.R. of R.A. No. 9184 on the procurement of goods;

2.    Disbursing Officers/SDOs submit liquidations of the CAs within the prescribed period provided in COA Circular No. 97-002; and refrain from transferring CA to another AO;

3.    Municipal Accountant:

•	prepare the schedule of all receivables, unliquidated cash advances, and fund transfers every quarter;
•	submit the duly signed Statement of Cash Advances and Liquidations of Andrew Vicente Garcellano, Ignacio D. Mendenilla and Faye L. Ormido as of December 31, 2018 and June 30, 2019; and
•	discontinue certifying cash advance vouchers intended for procurement of goods.

4.    LCE and the Municipal Accountant, in all instances, ensure that each provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 are strictly observed and that all cash advances are fully liquidated at the end of the year.

We recommended that the:

a.	Municipal Engineer and the MPDC (i) reevaluate and complete the list of infrastructure projects in the monitoring report and provide all the minimum required information on the implementation of each project; and (ii) immediately submit to the Audit Team the consolidated status report/information of all the infrastructure projects started, completed and still on-going as of December 31, 2018; 

b.	Municipal Engineer hasten the implementation of 28 projects and make sure that all infrastructure projects are strictly monitored and implemented in accordance with plans and schedules so that the intended beneficiaries could enjoy the benefits of these programs;

c.	LCE, ME and MPDC strictly comply with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 2013-004 regarding information and publicity of PPAs as well as the general provisions of succeeding GAAs on transparency in the status of implementation of PPAs;

d.	LCE (i) issue termination of contract to erring contractors who have negative slippage of ten percent (10%) or more in the completion of the work pursuant to Section III-A(2) of the Guidelines on Termination of Contracts; and (ii) cause the forfeiture of their performance security pursuant to Section 8.5 of the R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184; and

e.	Municipal Accountant and ME compute and impose liquidated damages against the six contractors of the 13 infrastructure projects which were completed beyond contract expiry date pursuant to Section 8 of the Contract Implementation Guidelines for the Procurement of Infrastructure Projects.

We recommended that the: 

1.	Municipal Engineer and the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) provide justification/proof that the two road concreting projects are distinct and no duplication of projects nor overlapping of funding had occurred;

2.	Members of the Sangguniang Bayan ensure that all changes in the annual budget such as re-appropriation of savings or realignment of projects or abandonment of PPAs to any item of expenditure under any class or to any new item of expenditure not included in the annual budget are covered by an appropriation ordinance or supplemental budget and submit the same to the Sangguniang Panlalawigan for review;

3.	Municipal Budget Officer certify the existence of valid appropriations only for expenditures supported with supplemental budget or appropriation ordinance duly authorized by the Sanggunian;

4.	Local Chief Executive compel the Municipal Engineer to submit the road maps/layouts, technical specifications, detailed estimates of the POW, as-built plans for the completed project/s, properly labeled photographs taken before, during and after construction of the project (with exact location coordinates) and the lacking supporting documents for each project mentioned in previous AOM No. Co2019-21 dated July 23, 2018 as these documents are necessary in the technical evaluation and inspection or validation of work accomplished for both projects; and 

5.	Municipal Engineer (a) prepare the detailed engineering design and POW in accordance with the DPWH issuances as well as the guidelines issued by the source agencies of fund transferred to the LGU; and (b) geotag pictures in every stages of infrastructure projects and provide the exact location of projects such as coordinate and station especially for road network projects for purposes of transparency and accurate reporting of project accomplishments.

We recommended that the:

1.	Municipal Treasurer (a) immediately demand payment of the rental fees and surcharges totaling ₱1,964,722.92 and submit proof of collection and deposit thereof to the Audit Team; and (b) update the records of collections per stallholder to address the variance from the rental payments confirmed by the lessees;

2.	Municipal Mayor cause the immediate cancellation/revocation of the lease contracts with delinquent stallholders.

We recommended that the:

1.	Local Chief Executive, as the head of the agency and the LDRRM Council (a) ensure that the portion of the LGU’s total LDRRMF pertaining to the 5% LDRRMF (30% Quick Response Fund and 70% Mitigation Fund) and unexpended balance of the LDRRMF in the preceding years within the five-year validity period of the STF are duly supported with the LDRRMFIP;

2.	Municipal Accountant (a) maintain SLs for the TL–DRRM account under the TF books for the transfers of the LGU’s unexpended DRRMF to the STF by year of transfer, receipts of NDRRMF by transferring agency and DRRMF from other LGUs and donors; (b) recognize the appropriate adjustments in the TF books to properly recognize the TL– DRRMF account for the receipts of amounts held in trust for the DRRMF; and (c) support the transfers of unexpended/unobligated balances with schedules such as the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of the DRRMF; 

3.	Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer reconcile the amount of unexpended balances per accounting reports and per budgetary reports in order to correctly determine the amount of unexpended balances of current and previous years’ unexpended QRF and DRRMF– MOOE to be transferred to the STF; and

4.	Municipal Accountant and Treasurer transfer the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF to the special trust fund pursuant to Section 21 of R.A. No. 10121 to ensure that funds are available for disaster risk reduction and management activities.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, as the head of the agency:

a.	vigorously seek approval of the SWMP from the Palawan Council for Sustainable Development;

b.	cause the immediate implementation of “Establishment of Sanitary Landfill” project;

c.	direct the SWM focal person to take actions and strategies to encourage the active participation of barangay officials by educating/training their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials and compostable wastes including the proper implementation of R.A. No. 9003;

d.	ensure that all garbage collectors and personnel dealing directly with solid wastes are provided with personal protective equipment and paraphernalia and enforce wearing them during their duty to protect them from the hazards of handling solid wastes; and

e.	consider the need to procure additional separate dump/garbage truck with appropriate cover of waste compartments taking into account the volume of garbage or waste materials from various hotels and other tourism establishments in the locality and ensure that all waste transport vehicles used by the LGU comply with Section 24 of R.A. No. 9003.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive, Municipal Development Council, Municipal Planning and Development and Budget Officers to improve their programs and projects implementation mechanism in order to ensure that the resources are managed in the most effective and efficient manner to meet the needs of the constituents and stakeholders of the Municipality. 

To improve planning and budgeting capabilities

Carefully plan and organize the project management plan. Often, project planning is ignored in favor of getting on with the work. However, many people fail to realize the value of a project plan in saving time, money and other problems;

Prepare APPs that are duly linked to AIP to ensure that every procurement is cost effective and efficient;

Enlist the help of other experts for technical knowledge on feasibility studies and project development;

Widen the network for collaboration; 

The guidelines and policies involving the implementation of programs or project should already been included in the planning and budgeting of these projects, duly approved by the Sangguniang Bayan;

To ensure that the plans are carried out

Clearly describe how the project will be managed and controlled in its delivery/execution phase;

Fast track the implementation of unimplemented PPAs;

Evaluate whether the programs and projects funded from prior years’ budget are still relevant otherwise revert the fund to other programs and projects which is more needed and applicable upon recommendation of the Local Chief Executive and approval by the Sanggunian concerned (Section 322 of RA No. 7160);

Make sure that the timeline set for every program/project is realistic and is strictly followed;

The timing of execution spells out the success of a program or a project;

To enhance accountability

a. The Municipal Development Council is advised strictly to monitor and evaluate PPAs (Section 112 of RA 7160) and provide for project support or program maintenance;

To improve economic efficiency in infrastructure projects.

a. Strictly abide  by  the  provisions  of Section 4, Annex A of IRR of RA 9184. Feasibility study and detailed engineering should be conducted first before implementing any project;

Support the Design Plans, Program of Works and Approved Budget Contract with a Detailed Unit Price Analysis;

Require the conduct of complete annual physical count of PPE in accordance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Vol. 1;

Require the maintenance of complete and accurate Equipment Ledger Cards/ PPELC for each inventory item pursuant to Section 488 (d) of the GAAM and the NGAS in order to promote effective monitoring and controls over PPE;

Require the reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records after the physical count;


Physical Inventory Reports shall be submitted to the Property Officer and COA Office for verification and reconciliation of the result of the physical inventory with the complete Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and the Property Cards maintained by the Accounting Office and Property Unit, respectively;

Require the renewal of Memorandum Receipt (MR) of Equipment every January of the third year after issue in accordance with Section 492 of GAAM Vol. 1; and

Comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.
